@article{Fischer2003,
abstract = {With the growing usage of the world-wide ICT networks, agent technologies and multiagent systems are attracting more and more attention, as they perform well in environments that are not necessarily well-structured and benevolent. Looking at the problem solving capacity of multiagent systems, emergent system behaviour is one of the most interesting phenomena, however, there is more to multiagent systems design than the interaction between a number of agents: For an effective system behaviour we need structure and organisation. But the organisa-tion of a multiagent systems is difficult to specify at design time in the face of a changing environment . This paper presents basic concepts for a theory of holonic multiagent systems to both provide a methodology for the recursive modelling of agent groups, and allow for dynamic reorganisation during runtime.},
annote = {-we shall use 'part' and 'element' of a system as interchangeable terms. the usage of 'part' is in a sense a homage to the mereological nature of the relation between the components of a system and the system itself; it also befits our emphasis in the holonic view of the systems we are concerned with. a thing to be clear is that although a part of a system is indeed a part of the underlying set for this system (for a specified partition), it is not true that any part of this set is a part of the corresponding system. in other words, it suffices to consider a partition of a set in order to define a subset of it as part, since for any such subset one can consider a partition made of the this part and its complement with respect to its superset. that is not immediately extendable to the parthood relation for systems since a part of a system must be a system [tem q ser msm? tenho que pensar isso melhor] (or an atomic part?) and not all subsets of an underlying set are indeed systems. 
-we shall make a distinction between concrete and abstract systems [ref]. it is also relevant to observe the distinction between models and actual systems [ref]. concrete systems are at best approximately isolated; they exist within a continuous hierarchy of nested systems.
-we shall allow parts of systems to be things other than systems 
[vou mesmo? pode ser, mas pra sistemas complexos isso muda:] "; but we will consider complex systems as lying within a holonic continuum. in this sense, a complex system is always an infinite object - which seems to be the case, although answers to questions such as if matter is infinitely divisible or not are relevant to the assesment of the adequacy of this metamodel/theoretical choice. that notwithstanding, considering that in principle this continuum could be infinite is practical. even if the Universe indeed 'ends' at a Plack length at its bottom limit and at something of about the inverse of its order of magnitute upwards, for most modeling of concrete systems, considering this range not limited is fine. as for the modeling of abstract systems, requiring this continuum to be limited would be too severe of a restriction, whereas letting it to be non-limited seems to pose no threat to the preciseness of the definition].

-ill call a nested system a holon; thus holons are systems that have a supersystem wherein they are parts and their parts are themselves (sub)systems. holons whose supersystem is not part of another system or whose subsystems are not composed of systems are said upper or lower terminal, outwards-limited and inwards-limited, respectively.

if a holon is both upper and lower terminal, it is said a limited holon. 

-the encompassing supersystem of an outwards-limited holon is said a holonic system‽, and is the same for every subsystem in the nesting hierarchy it encompasses.

-the parts of the parts of an inwards-limited holon are said atomic parts. 

-an infinite hierarchy of holons is said a holonic continuum.

-a finite hierarchy of holons is said a limited (holonic) continuum {talvez eu devesse chamar isso de holonic system}.

-notice that hierarchies can be holons, since nested systems are systems. indeed, a main goal of this work is to present a rigorous framework to consider different kinds and sizes of holons within the same hierarchy. the number or size (in the continuous case) of levels a finite nesting hierarchy has is called the order of the limited continuum. the number or size of levels a holon has is said its degree. a holon within a finite hierarchy of order N can have degree up to N-2 or N-2da. in this case, it is necessarily a terminal holon, and said maximal (in respect to this hierarchy). a holon whose degree is 0 is said minimal.

-holons are identified by their levels in a hierarchy, and are unique in this sense. the holon of level a must figure as a holonic layer of a holon that ranges from a-e to a+e. we shall use "level" to refer to a holon within a hierarchy and layer to refer to a holon when it is composing another holon. the rigorous definitions of these concepts should make the difference clearer.

-ill allow systems to have parts of various kinds, and holons (must be composed?) must be of a different kind than any element of its transitive closure minus itself. notice that this restriction implies that holons are also of a different type than any of its holonic layers, since any of them is element of this transitive closure.
-we shall define an operation that compresses holons (reducing their degree) and their correponding hierarchy (reducing its order). this operation should be invertible.
-we shall define an equivalence relation between hierarchies that are obtained by "compressing" levels. essentially, two hierarchies should be equivalent if they can be obtained by the compressing operation or its inverse. specifically, \forall a, b \in Hierarchies: [(aRb <=> C(a) = b) => (bRa \land C^{-1}(b) = a)] \land [(aRb <=> C^{-1}(a) = b) => (bRa \land C(b) = a)].
-it is relevant to observe that the relation "is a sub/superholon of" is not transitive, nor is the relation `part of'. we agree with [ref] (citar o paper de mereologia que fala disso) when it is said that the parthood relation is not transitive. this become evident under the context of systems theory. if one is to consider a part of a system as the same as an element and the 
-we must consider the concepts of emergent hierarchy and emergent supersystem.
-we must perfunctorily discuss the idea of centralization and decentralization.
-we 
-atomic parts as implicit systems?

further research

>extensions
-a natural extension is to generalize this simplified hierarchical structure to one that allows arbitrary interlevel interactions. 
-another is one that does not imposes unicity over types. in this sense, a kind of system can be present at multiple levels in a hierarachy.

>improving formalism
-study the benefits of the proper use of mereology
-proper adequacy to the usage of the dynamical systems theory tools for better qualitative analysis

